## Collecting Twitter data

Before getting started with collecting data from Twitter, we need to create an access token that allows us to communicate with the Twitter API. The authentication process is summarized here:

https://rtweet.info/articles/auth.html

We'll use the token/secret method, i.e. you need to copy and paste four keys from your Twitter developer page to the `create_token()` function.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin  -->

```r
# The following keys are provided for testing purposes only

create_token(
  app = "Twitter API String Tracker",
  consumer_key = "rCVjASAtmlConQfTd1R6XjOTx",
  consumer_secret = "ysYiFKXE2rdE2LOH2dp7Ow1tiiciNBR1Bz5uXMPKJghd1cLbkE",
  access_token = "843482256803020809-K20s6YXiVp6DEohoK0AUo11n3mLlPXI",
  access_secret = "zWaW1TE4OcUL8TcLqGNQxyo1ja68dmg2eIoU6lqQmOeMq"
)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-output-begin  -->


The access information will be stored locally and re-loaded in new R sessions. We can check whether an access token is currently loaded by running `get_token()`.   


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuZ2V0X3Rva2VuKClcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
get_token()
```

### Search tweets and users

The `rtweet` package offers many features for searching and collecting Twitter data. As an example, `search_tweets()` allows us to search and retrieve tweets by keywords.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuP3NlYXJjaF90d2VldHNcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
?search_tweets
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Among other options, we can specify the number of desired tweets to be returned via `n`. Note that the default `type` of search results to return is "recent".


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuY2hpY2Fnb190d2VldHMgPC0gc2VhcmNoX3R3ZWV0cyhcIiNDaGljYWdvUG9saWNlXCIsIG4gPSAxMDApXG5jaGljYWdvX3R3ZWV0c1xuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
chicago_tweets <- search_tweets("#ChicagoPolice", n = 100)
chicago_tweets
```

### Stream tweets

A major functionality of the `rtweet` is the option to live stream tweets. As an example, we can collect a 'random' sample of Tweets for 10 seconds as follows.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc3RyZWFtX3R3ZWV0cyhcbiAgcSA9IFwiXCIsXG4gIHRpbWVvdXQgPSAxMCxcbiAgZmlsZV9uYW1lID0gXCJzYW1wbGUuanNvblwiLFxuICBwYXJzZSA9IEZBTFNFXG4pXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
stream_tweets(
  q = "",
  timeout = 10,
  file_name = "sample.json",
  parse = FALSE
)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Since the results were written to a local json file, we need to load and parse them to make them accessible in R.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxuc2FtcGxlIDwtIHBhcnNlX3N0cmVhbShcInNhbXBsZS5qc29uXCIpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
sample <- parse_stream("sample.json")
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->

```r
ts_plot(sample, by = "secs")
```

## Exploring Twitter data

In this section we check whether the top words in the tweets that were collected in the previous step match with the search keywords.

First, we need to clean the tweets. This includes deleting links using regex and `gsub()`. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxua2V5d29yZHMkdGV4dCA8LSBnc3ViKFwiaHR0cC4qXCIsIFwiXCIsIGtleXdvcmRzJHRleHQpXG5rZXl3b3JkcyR0ZXh0IDwtIGdzdWIoXCJodHRwcy4qXCIsIFwiXCIsIGtleXdvcmRzJHRleHQpXG5rZXl3b3JkcyR0ZXh0IDwtIGdzdWIoXCImYW1wO1wiLCBcIiZcIiwga2V5d29yZHMkdGV4dClcbmBgYCJ9 -->

```r
keywords$text <- gsub("http.*", "", keywords$text)
keywords$text <- gsub("https.*", "", keywords$text)
keywords$text <- gsub("&amp;", "&", keywords$text)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Next, we remove punctuation, convert to lowercase, and separate the words.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxua2V5d29yZHNfY2xlYW4gPC0ga2V5d29yZHMgJT4lXG4gIHNlbGVjdCh0ZXh0KSAlPiVcbiAgdW5uZXN0X3Rva2Vucyh3b3JkLCB0ZXh0KVxuYGBgIn0= -->

```r
keywords_clean <- keywords %>%
  select(text) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


Lastly, we delete stopwords using a stopword lexicon from the `tidytext` package. 


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxubnJvdyhrZXl3b3Jkc19jbGVhbilcblxuc3RvcHdkcyA8LSBnZXRfc3RvcHdvcmRzKFwiZW5cIilcbmtleXdvcmRzX2NsZWFuZXIgPC0ga2V5d29yZHNfY2xlYW4gJT4lXG4gIGFudGlfam9pbihzdG9wd2RzKVxuXG5ucm93KGtleXdvcmRzX2NsZWFuZXIpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
nrow(keywords_clean)

stopwds <- get_stopwords("en")
keywords_cleaner <- keywords_clean %>%
  anti_join(stopwds)

nrow(keywords_cleaner)
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->


<!-- rnb-text-begin -->


We can now plot the top 15 words based on the cleaned tweet text.


<!-- rnb-text-end -->


<!-- rnb-chunk-begin -->


<!-- rnb-source-begin eyJkYXRhIjoiYGBgclxua2V5d29yZHNfY2xlYW5lciAlPiVcbiAgY291bnQod29yZCwgc29ydCA9IFRSVUUpICU+JVxuICB0b3BfbigxNSkgJT4lXG4gIG11dGF0ZSh3b3JkID0gcmVvcmRlcih3b3JkLCBuKSkgJT4lXG4gIGdncGxvdCgpICtcbiAgZ2VvbV9jb2woYWVzKHggPSB3b3JkLCB5ID0gbikpICtcbiAgY29vcmRfZmxpcCgpXG5gYGAifQ== -->

```r
keywords_cleaner %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(15) %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = word, y = n)) +
  coord_flip()
```

<!-- rnb-source-end -->

<!-- rnb-chunk-end -->
